webpackJsonp([0xd8c078e7e506],{476:function(e,a){e.exports={pathContext:{docHtml:'<h1 id="argo-server"><a href="#argo-server" aria-hidden="true" class="anchor"><svg aria-hidden="true" height="16" version="1.1" viewBox="0 0 16 16" width="16"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z"></path></svg></a>Argo Server</h1>\n<p><img src="assets/alpha.svg" alt="alpha"></p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>v2.5 and after</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>The Argo Server is a server that exposes an API and UI for workflows. You\'ll need to use this if you want to <a href="offloading-large-workflows.html">offload large workflows</a> or the <a href="workflow-archive.html">workflow archive</a>.</p>\n<p>You can run this in either "hosted" or "local" mode.</p>\n<p>It replaces the Argo UI.</p>\n<h2 id="hosted-mode"><a href="#hosted-mode" aria-hidden="true" class="anchor"><svg aria-hidden="true" height="16" version="1.1" viewBox="0 0 16 16" width="16"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z"></path></svg></a>Hosted Mode</h2>\n<p>Use this mode if:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>You want a drop-in replacement for the Argo UI.</li>\n<li>If you need to prevent users from directly accessing the database.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Hosted mode is provided as part of the standard <a href="../manifests">manifests</a>, <a href="../manifests/base/argo-server/argo-server-deployment.yaml">specifically in argo-server-deployment.yaml</a> .</p>\n<h2 id="local-mode"><a href="#local-mode" aria-hidden="true" class="anchor"><svg aria-hidden="true" height="16" version="1.1" viewBox="0 0 16 16" width="16"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z"></path></svg></a>Local Mode</h2>\n<p>Use this mode if:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>You want something that does not require complex set-up. </li>\n<li>You do not need to run a database.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>To run locally:</p>\n<pre><code>argo server\n</code></pre>\n<p>This will start a server on port 2746 which you can view at <a href="http://localhost:2746%5D">http://localhost:2746</a>.</p>\n<h2 id="options"><a href="#options" aria-hidden="true" class="anchor"><svg aria-hidden="true" height="16" version="1.1" viewBox="0 0 16 16" width="16"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z"></path></svg></a>Options</h2>\n<h3 id="auth-mode"><a href="#auth-mode" aria-hidden="true" class="anchor"><svg aria-hidden="true" height="16" version="1.1" viewBox="0 0 16 16" width="16"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z"></path></svg></a>Auth Mode</h3>\n<p>You can choose which kube config the server uses: </p>\n<ul>\n<li>"server" - in hosted mode, use the kube config of service account, in local mode, use your local kube config.  </li>\n<li>"client" - requires client to provide their Kubernetes bearer token and use that.</li>\n<li>"hybrid" - use the client token if provided, fallback to the server token if note.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>By default, the server will start with auth mode of "client" (highest security).</p>\n<h3 id="managed-namespace"><a href="#managed-namespace" aria-hidden="true" class="anchor"><svg aria-hidden="true" height="16" version="1.1" viewBox="0 0 16 16" width="16"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z"></path></svg></a>Managed Namespace</h3>\n<p>See <a href="managed-namespace.html">managed namespace</a>.</p>',docPath:"argo/docs/argo-server",proj:"argo"}}}});
